{"title_page": "Uri Mayer", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=September 2014}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:MayerWeb.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Uri Mayer]] -->'''Uri Mayer''' (born August 4, 1946 in [[T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]], [[Romania]]) is Romanian-born [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[violist]] and [[Conducting|conductor]].\n\nMayer moved to [[Israel]] at a young age, and studied at the Conservatory of Music of Tel-Aviv and the University of Tel-Aviv.   His conducting debut took place in 1964 while he was still in high school.\n\nHe was Assistant Conductor of the National Youth Orchestra of Israel (1964-1970), and was a member of the [[Israel Philharmonic]] (1967-1968).  After winning a scholarship in 1968, he moved to [[New York City]] to study with Jean Morel at the [[Juilliard School]].  He was Assistant Conductor of the [[New York Youth Symphony]] and principal violist with [[Leopold Stokowski]]\u2019s [[American Symphony Orchestra]]. In 1970, he became assistant principal violist of the [[Montreal Symphony Orchestra]], and in 1980, he became Associate Conductor.\n\nFrom 1981 to 1994, Mayer was Music Director of the [[Edmonton Symphony Orchestra]].  He was also Principal Conductor of Orchestra London (1988-1994), Artistic Adviser to The Israel Sinfonietta [[Beersheba]] (1991-1999), and Principal Conductor of Kansai Philharmonic (1994-2000).\n\nMayer currently resides in [[Toronto]] where he is on Faculty at the University of Toronto <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://music.utoronto.ca/our-people.php?fid=256 | title=University of Toronto - Faculty of Music - Our People}}</ref> after previously serving as Resident Conductor of the Royal Conservatory Orchestra.\n\n*{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Edmonton Symphony Orchestra|Music Directors, Edmonton Symphony Orchestra]] | before=[[Pierre H\u00e9tu]] | years=1981&ndash;1994 | after=[[Grzegorz Nowak (conductor)|Grzegorz Nowak]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web\n  | last = Bowman\n  | first = Durrell \n  | title = Uri Mayer\n  | publisher = Encyclopedia of Music in Canada\n  | url = http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/uri-mayer-emc/}}\n*{{cite web\n |last        = Baker\n |first       = D.T\n |title       = Edmonton Symphony Music Directors\n |publisher   = Edmonton Symphony Orchestra website\n |url         = http://www.edmontonsymphony.com/AbouttheESO/HistoryoftheESO/tabid/261/Default.aspx\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081220082501/http://edmontonsymphony.com/AbouttheESO/HistoryoftheESO/tabid/261/Default.aspx\n |archivedate = 2008-12-20\n}}\n* {{cite web\n  | last = Kaylor\n  | first = Management\n  | title = Kaylor Management Inc.\n  | publisher = KMI\n  | url = http://www.hughkaylor.com/UriMayer.html}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayer, Uri}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Canadian classical violists]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Romanian emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:People from T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=September 2014}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:MayerWeb.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Uri Mayer]] -->'''Uri Mayer''' (born August 4, 1946 in [[T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]], [[Romania]]) is Romanian-born [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[violist]] and [[Conducting|conductor]].\n\nMayer moved to [[Israel]] at a young age, and studied at the Conservatory of Music of Tel-Aviv and the University of Tel-Aviv.   His conducting debut took place in 1964 while he was still in high school.\n\nHe was Assistant Conductor of the National Youth Orchestra of Israel (1964-1970), and was a member of the [[Israel Philharmonic]] (1967-1968).  After winning a scholarship in 1968, he moved to [[New York City]] to study with Jean Morel at the [[Juilliard School]].  He was Assistant Conductor of the [[New York Youth Symphony]] and principal violist with [[Leopold Stokowski]]\u2019s [[American Symphony Orchestra]]. In 1970, he became assistant principal violist of the [[Montreal Symphony Orchestra]], and in 1980, he became Associate Conductor.\n\nFrom 1981 to 1994, Mayer was Music Director of the [[Edmonton Symphony Orchestra]].  He was also Principal Conductor of Orchestra London (1988-1994), Artistic Adviser to The Israel Sinfonietta [[Beersheba]] (1991-1999), and Principal Conductor of Kansai Philharmonic (1994-2000).\n\nMayer currently resides in [[Toronto]] where he is on Faculty at the University of Toronto <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://music.utoronto.ca/our-people.php?fid=256 | title=University of Toronto - Faculty of Music - Our People}}</ref> after previously serving as Resident Conductor of the Royal Conservatory Orchestra.\n\n*{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Edmonton Symphony Orchestra|Music Directors, Edmonton Symphony Orchestra]] | before=[[Pierre H\u00e9tu]] | years=1981&ndash;1994 | after=[[Grzegorz Nowak (conductor)|Grzegorz Nowak]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{cite web\n  | last = Bowman\n  | first = Durrell \n  | title = Uri Mayer\n  | publisher = Encyclopedia of Music in Canada\n  | url = http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/uri-mayer-emc/}}\n\n{{cite web\n |last        = Baker\n |first       = D.T\n |title       = Edmonton Symphony Music Directors\n |publisher   = Edmonton Symphony Orchestra website\n |url         = http://www.edmontonsymphony.com/AbouttheESO/HistoryoftheESO/tabid/261/Default.aspx\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081220082501/http://edmontonsymphony.com/AbouttheESO/HistoryoftheESO/tabid/261/Default.aspx\n |archivedate = 2008-12-20\n}}\n\n{{cite web\n  | last = Kaylor\n  | first = Management\n  | title = Kaylor Management Inc.\n  | publisher = KMI\n  | url = http://www.hughkaylor.com/UriMayer.html}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayer, Uri}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Canadian classical violists]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Romanian emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:People from T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:list", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uri_Mayer"}
{"title_page": "Lakhahi", "text_new": "{{moresources|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Village in Uttar Pradesh, India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n'''Lakhahi''' is a village and a large [[Gram panchayat]] in [[Dhaurehra]] tehsil [[Lakhimpur Kheri district]], Uttar Pradesh state, [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mapsofindia.com/villages/uttar-pradesh/kheri/dhaurahara/lakhahi.html|title=Map of Lakhahi Village in Dhaurahara Tehsil, Kheri, Uttar Pradesh|website=Mapsofindia.com|url-status=live|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> It is a erstwhile Independent Princely State and a Zamindari Estate.  \n\nLakhahi was earlier famous for Ketki Flower.  \n\n<br />   \n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Lakhahi\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{Flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = State\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = District\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Lakhimpur Kheri district|Lakhimpur Kheri]]\n| governing_body                  = [[Gram panchayat]]\n| founder                         = Maharaja Shri Akhai Raj Singh Rathore{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n| registration_plate              = UP- 31\n| population_total                = 5510\n| settlement_type                 = Village\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| government_type                 = [[Sarpanch]] (Pradhan)\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|28.16|N|80.97|E| display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map                     = India Uttar Pradesh#India#Asia\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Uttar Pradesh, India\n| pushpin_label_position          = Right\n| official_name                   = \n| image_shield                    = PSX_20190910_220033_edited.jpg\n| translit_lang1                  = \n| website                         = \n| established_date                = c.1461\n| native_name_lang                = \n| extinct_date                    = 1 July 1952\n| established_title               = Sovereign monarchy\n| extinct_title                   = Abolition of Monarchy\n| established_title1              = \n| established_title2              = \n| established_date1               = \n| established_date2               = \n| established_date3               = \n| established_title3              = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Lakhimpur Kheri district]]\n\n\n{{LakhimpurKheri-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{moresources|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Village in Uttar Pradesh, India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n'''Lakhahi''' is a village and a large [[Gram panchayat]] in [[Dhaurehra]] tehsil [[Lakhimpur Kheri district]], Uttar Pradesh state, [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mapsofindia.com/villages/uttar-pradesh/kheri/dhaurahara/lakhahi.html|title=Map of Lakhahi Village in Dhaurahara Tehsil, Kheri, Uttar Pradesh|website=Mapsofindia.com|url-status=live|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> It is a erstwhile Independent Princely State and a Zamindari Estate.  \n\nLakhahi was earlier famous for Ketki Flower.  \n\n<br />   \n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Lakhahi\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{Flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = State\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = District\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Lakhimpur Kheri district|Lakhimpur Kheri]]\n| governing_body                  = [[Gram panchayat]]\n| founder                         = Maharaja Shri Akhai Raj Singh Rathore{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n| registration_plate              = UP- 31\n| population_total                = 5510\n| settlement_type                 = Village\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| governme